{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:40:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:40:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15773"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115014"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97020"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7052"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22678"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115014"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe scrotum contains several distinct layers that protect and support the testes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly lists the layers of the scrotum from the skin in to the tunica vaginalis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cremasteric muscle and fascia \u003E external spermatic fascia \u003E dartos muscle \u003E internal spermatic fascia","Dartos muscle \u003E cremasteric muscle and fascia \u003E external spermatic fascia \u003E internal spermatic fascia","Dartos muscle \u003E external spermatic fascia \u003E cremasteric muscle and fascia \u003E internal spermatic fascia","External spermatic fascia \u003E cremasteric muscle and fascia \u003E dartos muscle \u003E internal spermatic fascia","External spermatic fascia \u003E dartos muscle \u003E cremasteric muscle and fascia \u003E internal spermatic fascia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct order of the layers of the scrotum from superficial to deep is: skin (most superficial), dartos muscle (smooth muscle that regulates scrotal temperature), external spermatic fascia (continuation of external oblique aponeurosis), cremasteric muscle and fascia (derived from internal oblique muscle), internal spermatic fascia (continuation of transversalis fascia), and tunica vaginalis (deepest layer, derived from processus vaginalis). The processus vaginalis is a developmental structure that normally obliterates, with its remnant forming the tunica vaginalis. Failure of obliteration can lead to indirect inguinal hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDartos muscle \u0026gt; external spermatic fascia \u0026gt; cremasteric muscle and fascia \u0026gt; internal spermatic fascia\u003C/strong\u003E follows the correct anatomical sequence from the dartos muscle immediately beneath the skin through to the internal spermatic fascia just superficial to the tunica vaginalis. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The layers of the scrotum from superficial to deep are: skin, dartos muscle, external spermatic fascia, cremasteric muscle and fascia, internal spermatic fascia, and tunica vaginalis.","The processus vaginalis normally obliterates during development, becoming the tunica vaginalis."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press.","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media.","Dwyer ME, Salgado CJ, Lightner DJ. Normal penile, scrotal, and perineal anatomy with reconstructive considerations. Semin Plast Surg. 2011 Aug;25(3):179-88. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1281487. PMID: 22851909; PMCID: PMC3312188."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97020"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15773"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97020"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T19:09:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T19:09:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Rememb